00:12:10.750 --> 00:12:11.150
&gt;&gt; Dr. Michael Chorost: Okay.

00:12:11.150 --> 00:12:15.370
So the implant picks up the radio
signal and its job is to send

00:12:15.370 --> 00:12:20.880
that signal down this wire
which terminates in a string

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:22.600
of electrodes inside the cochlea.

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:27.790
In this close-up, you can see that
string of electrodes [inaudible]

00:12:27.790 --> 00:12:32.730
up inside the cochlea and here
are the little electrode plates.

00:12:32.730 --> 00:12:35.650
Those are tiny electrodes
made of platinum and iridium,

00:12:35.650 --> 00:12:41.660
and those electrodes are strobed
on and off in complex patterns

00:12:41.660 --> 00:12:46.510
to activate the nerves inside
the center of the cochlea,

00:12:46.510 --> 00:12:50.130
so this is the beginning of that.

00:12:50.130 --> 00:12:54.740
So as these things trigger on
and off sending little shocks,

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:58.180
they force the nerves inside
the center of the cochlea

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:02.560
to send sound information down
the auditory nerve to the brain.

00:13:02.560 --> 00:13:06.840
So that's what a cochlear
implant does.

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:10.500
It replaces the mechanical
system of the inner ear

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:14.470
with an electronic system
that sends digital information

00:13:14.470 --> 00:13:18.270
into the auditory cortex
of the brain.

00:13:18.270 --> 00:13:20.550
Amazing technology.

00:13:20.550 --> 00:13:24.070
So that's cochlear implant 101.

