to getting low frequency sounds,

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:52.750
so the software breaks
up sound by frequency.

00:16:52.750 --> 00:16:56.740
It takes all the high pitches
and sends them down here.

00:16:56.740 --> 00:17:00.610
It takes all the low pitches
and it sends them down there.

00:17:00.610 --> 00:17:05.440
So it takes sound apart kind of the
way a coin sorter would take coins

00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:07.440
and sort them by the
size of the coin,

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:10.260
and it will send the
appropriate frequencies

00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:13.730
to the appropriate
part of the cochlea.

00:17:13.730 --> 00:17:17.400
So you may wonder, how many
people have this technology.

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:18.130
Is it new?

00:17:18.130 --> 00:17:19.640
Is it experimental?

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:21.010
The answer is, no, it's not.

00:17:21.010 --> 00:17:23.550
It's been around the 1990s.

00:17:23.550 --> 00:17:29.070
And there's about 219,000
people with implants worldwide

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:34.990
since the technology became
commercial in the very late 1980s.

00:17:34.990 --> 00:17:38.770
So you may wonder, is
that a lot or a little?

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:41.310
Well, to give you a
little bit of perspective,

00:17:41.310 --> 00:17:46.270
in the United States alone
there are about 500,000 people

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:49.860
who have hearing losses severe
enough to make them candidates

00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:55.350
to get a cochlear implant; half
a million in this country alone,

00:17:55.350 --> 00:17:58.180
and yet worldwide there's
less than a quarter

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:00.900
of a million implant users.

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:04.730
So what that tells you is that
this technology is still very much

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:07.910
underused, that there are
many people who could benefit

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:10.950
from this technology
who don't have it.

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:15.380
And there are many reasons
for that, economic reasons,

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:19.880
reasons of knowledge, reasons of
what doctors believe and so forth.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:23.130
So even though the technology
has been around for decades,

00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:26.500
it is still very much
an emergent technology.

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:31.530
So now, let me give you an
inkling of what the world sounds

00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:34.030
like to me with a cochlear implant.

00:18:34.030 --> 00:18:38.800
So I'm going to play you
a couple of sound files

00:18:38.800 --> 00:18:42.290
and let me tell you
what this is about.

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:46.940
You're going to hear what
sounds like an English sentence

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:51.350
that has been electronically
filtered to resemble the output

00:18:51.350 --> 00:18:55.440
of a cochlear implant, and your
challenge will be to figure

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:58.680
out what the sentence is.

00:18:58.680 --> 00:19:02.240
I'm going to play you a couple
of versions of that sentence.

00:19:02.240 --> 00:19:07.320
The first version, the four-channel
version, roughly corresponds

00:19:07.320 --> 00:19:09.570
to what some of the
very earliest users

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:12.880
of experimental cochlear
implants heard,

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:17.640
because at that time they had
only four or six electrodes.

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:21.830
They were very primitive
devices by today's standards.

00:19:21.830 --> 00:19:25.720
When my first cochlear
implant was first turned on,

00:19:25.720 --> 00:19:30.030
the software gave me the
equivalent of eight electrodes.

00:19:30.030 --> 00:19:32.670
I'm simplifying here because at

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:37.630 position:56%
that point even though there were 16
electrodes in the electrode array,

00:19:37.630 --> 00:19:40.400
the software treated
each pair of them

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.820
as if it was a single electrode.

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:47.550
So I got, in effect, eight
electrodes worth of information.

00:19:47.550 --> 00:19:51.890
Then a year later, I got new
software that made each electrode

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:56.190
in individual channel,
giving me 16 channels.

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:58.810
So I'm going to play
you four, eight and 16.

00:19:58.810 --> 00:20:01.310
Let's see if you can figure
out what the sentence is.

00:20:01.310 --> 00:20:06.290
&gt;&gt; [Sound recording]
I like to play tennis.

