&gt;&gt; Dr. Michael Chorost:
Big difference, right?

00:22:20.680 --> 00:22:24.220
So there are two lessons to
be drawn from this slide.

00:22:24.220 --> 00:22:26.430
The first lesson [background
sounds] is

00:22:26.430 --> 00:22:30.350
that a cochlear implant does not
give you super human hearing.

00:22:30.350 --> 00:22:35.240
It is not Jamie Summer's Bionic
Woman, X-man kind of hearing.

00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:38.290
On the other hand,
it is usable hearing.

00:22:38.290 --> 00:22:41.270
It allowed me to use the
telephone, listen to the radio,

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:45.400
have conversations, even in
noisy rooms and in restaurants.

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:48.480
So that's a lesson to be
drawn from that slide.

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:52.640
Okay. So now we've done
cochlear implant 101 --

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:56.580
cyborg 101, or rather,
modern-day cyborg 101.

00:22:56.580 --> 00:23:00.390
So we'll talk about what this
technology means for the future.

00:23:00.390 --> 00:23:06.450
So let's talk about some emerging
neuroprosthetic technologies.

00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:09.860
So this is a video --
there's no sound in the video,

00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:13.450
it's just the video -- that
shows a double amputee.

00:23:13.450 --> 00:23:15.110
He lost both of his arms.

00:23:15.110 --> 00:23:17.060
He was an electrical linesman.

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:19.580
He was electrocuted;
both of his arms had

00:23:19.580 --> 00:23:22.240
to be amputated at the shoulder.

00:23:22.240 --> 00:23:27.340
So people are working on building
externally wearable prosthetic arms

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:29.880
for him to use.

00:23:33.210 --> 00:23:38.170
So, these arms are getting their
information from those electrodes

00:23:38.170 --> 00:23:41.260
that you can see on his
back; they are picking

00:23:41.260 --> 00:23:43.840
up the twitches of his muscles.

00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:47.710
And in fact, surgeons have actually
moved around the nerve [inaudible]

00:23:47.710 --> 00:23:51.000
to different places on his
back and his shoulder so that

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:54.200
when he imagines a given
set of muscle motions,

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:58.270
muscle will actually twitch
in his back and on his chest

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:00.870
and the electrodes pick
up those twitchings --

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:04.330
those twitches and they figure
out what he is trying to do

00:24:04.330 --> 00:24:06.540
and they make the arm do it.

00:24:06.540 --> 00:24:09.830
So this is an example of
what's state-of-the-art

00:24:09.830 --> 00:24:11.750
in prosthetic arms today.

00:24:11.750 --> 00:24:15.820
And you'll notice, by the
way, he's wearing goggles,

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:18.960
so they're clearly not
entirely sure of the safety

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:21.510
of these devices yet [laughter].

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:27.150
So let me tell you
two things about this.

00:24:27.150 --> 00:24:30.380
On the one hand, it's
incredibly impressive.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:33.060
He's actually controlling
this thing fairly well.

00:24:33.060 --> 00:24:38.000
On the other hand, it
still falls very far short

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:41.020
of reproducing a natural arm.

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:45.000
First of all, he gets no
sensory feedback from the arm,

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:48.710
so he only knows where
it is by looking at it.

00:24:48.710 --> 00:24:52.110
Second, the software is
only sophisticated enough

00:24:52.110 --> 00:24:55.650
to decode one motion at a
time, so, it's hard for them

00:24:55.650 --> 00:24:58.730
to just move smoothly and
do several things at a time.

00:24:58.730 --> 00:25:01.320
It's more like he's
got to move the elbow,

00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:03.640
move the wrist and move the elbow.

00:25:03.640 --> 00:25:08.790
He has to decompose the motion
and execute them one at a time.

00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:13.270
So it is both impressive and
underwhelming at the same time.

00:25:13.270 --> 00:25:15.100
So this shows you kind
of the cutting edge

00:25:15.100 --> 00:25:18.630
of how much information we can
get of what the brain wants

00:25:18.630 --> 00:25:21.460
and reading muscles on
the outside of the body.

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:24.610
There's nothing going on with
the technology in his brain

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:27.440
for this particular technology.

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:32.320
So what if you could
go to the brain?

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:35.590
Now, this is something that I
wrote about in a story I wrote

00:25:35.590 --> 00:25:40.260 position:56%
for "Wired Magazine" last year, it's
called "Waiting for the Bionic Man."

00:25:40.260 --> 00:25:43.120
So you can actually just find it
online by doing a Google search

00:25:43.120 --> 00:25:50.150
for "wired bionic arm" and my last
name, "Chorost," C-H-O-R-O-S-T.

00:25:50.150 --> 00:25:55.270
It's how I explored some of the
things that prosthetic arms can do,

00:25:55.270 --> 00:25:58.840
but also why it is still so
difficult to make them behave

00:25:58.840 --> 00:26:02.430
as well as naturally
performing arms.

00:26:02.430 --> 00:26:06.670
Okay. People are trying to get into
the brain itself to figure out how

00:26:06.670 --> 00:26:09.370
to read information out of
the brain because that's

00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:10.880
where the information is.

00:26:10.880 --> 00:26:16.160
It's like this is my [inaudible]
because that's where the money is.

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:19.280
This is why researchers are trying
to get in the brain because that's

00:26:19.280 --> 00:26:22.800
where the code is that tells you
what the brain is trying to do.

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:27.260
So this is very primitive
technology that I actually tried.

00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:30.790
Now, that's me wearing
a cat with electrodes

00:26:30.790 --> 00:26:35.770
and what this does is I'm
looking at that computer screen

00:26:35.770 --> 00:26:39.620
and various letters are
flashing on and off.

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:42.260
It's flashing one letter at a time.

00:26:42.260 --> 00:26:46.140
And I'm just looking at a letter
and waiting for it to flash.

00:26:46.140 --> 00:26:50.240
When it flashes, there's a
perceptible signal that goes

00:26:50.240 --> 00:26:54.670
on in the visual cortex where the
visual cortex is saying, "Hey,

00:26:54.670 --> 00:26:56.720
something just happened."

00:26:56.720 --> 00:27:00.580
When that happens that a peer
knows that what I was looking

00:27:00.580 --> 00:27:04.060
at it has just been lit
up and it puts that letter

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:07.190
on the screen up on top here.

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:09.840
So it's actually very
simple technology.

00:27:09.840 --> 00:27:13.960
It's just looking for
activation in the visual cortex

00:27:13.960 --> 00:27:15.610
and it works surprisingly well.

00:27:15.610 --> 00:27:19.420
I was able spell out "Hello
out there" just by looking

00:27:19.420 --> 00:27:21.980 position:56%
at different letters on this screen.

00:27:21.980 --> 00:27:23.920
So it's a really interesting
technology

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:27.170 position:56%
but it's still external to the body.

00:27:27.170 --> 00:27:30.610
Okay. What if I go inside?

00:27:30.610 --> 00:27:33.250
Well, this is a new video
-- well, not that new.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:35.980
It's about two years old now.

00:27:35.980 --> 00:27:41.640
This is of a woman who is
paraplegic, completely paralyzed,

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:46.450
and she had implants installed
in her brain in the motor cortex,

00:27:46.450 --> 00:27:49.450
the part that controls the arm.

00:27:49.450 --> 00:27:53.330
And that implant is being used

00:27:53.330 --> 00:27:56.130
to drive the robotic
arm that you see here.

00:27:56.130 --> 00:28:00.110
So you can see on the top of
her head, that is the plug

00:28:00.110 --> 00:28:01.930
that is actually picking

00:28:01.930 --> 00:28:06.150 position:56%
up electrical signals put inside
her motor cortex, data is being sent

00:28:06.150 --> 00:28:08.730
to the computer and the
computer is trying to figure

00:28:08.730 --> 00:28:11.480
out from her brain
activity what she is trying

00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:13.700
to do with the robotic arm.

00:28:13.700 --> 00:28:21.940
And you can see that A, it
does kind of work and, B,

00:28:21.940 --> 00:28:24.720
it's not ready for prime time.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:30.240
So, again, we have that combination
of amazing and underwhelming

00:28:30.240 --> 00:28:37.510
and you will see in a moment
she will get it up to her mouth.

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:46.280
[ Pause ]

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:50.420
So I was told by John Donahue
[assumed spelling] who is the PI,

00:28:50.420 --> 00:28:54.280
the principal investigator, of this
study that this was the first time

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:58.000
since she had been paralyzed that
she was able to pick up a cup

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.510
and bring it to her
own mouth by herself.

00:29:00.510 --> 00:29:27.010
[ Pause ]

00:29:27.010 --> 00:29:28.010
[ Laughter ]

00:29:28.010 --> 00:29:30.010
[ Inaudible Conversations ]

00:29:30.010 --> 00:29:37.060
[ Pause ]

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:39.510
Now, she's got to get it
back down on the table.

00:29:39.510 --> 00:29:53.010
[ Pause ]

00:29:53.010 --> 00:29:58.040
[ Applause ]

00:29:58.040 --> 00:30:02.070
So it's really quite amazing
what the technology can do,

00:30:02.070 --> 00:30:04.380
but we're still trying to
grapple with the question

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:08.480
of how much further can you go
with this kind of technology.

00:30:08.480 --> 00:30:13.230
Well, I'll show you a short clip
from a TV show that I wrote back

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:17.640
in 2007 asking, well, how
do you get inside the brain?

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:19.850
And here's one possible way.

00:30:19.850 --> 00:30:25.570
And this video does have
audio, so if you can't hear it,

00:30:25.570 --> 00:30:28.950
raise your hand and
I'll turn the volume up.

