So, a year or two ago I wrote
another story in "Wired"

00:32:14.510 --> 00:32:17.920
about a technology
called optogenetics.

00:32:17.920 --> 00:32:19.990
It's not a very glamorous
sounding name.

00:32:19.990 --> 00:32:22.230
Optogenetics, what's that?

00:32:22.230 --> 00:32:25.440
What it is is its using light

00:32:25.440 --> 00:32:29.810
to make genetically altered
neurons fire or stop firing.

00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:32.700
So let me explain a little bit
further what optogenetics is

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.560
all about.

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:37.350 position:56%
With a technology like optogenetics,

00:32:37.350 --> 00:32:40.230
you start by putting
altered genes --

00:32:40.230 --> 00:32:43.180
or rather, you start by
putting genes inside the neurons

00:32:43.180 --> 00:32:45.640
in a particular part of the brain.

00:32:45.640 --> 00:32:47.210
Well, what genes?

00:32:47.210 --> 00:32:49.650
You take genes from plants.

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:51.330
What genes from plants?

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:56.150
You take the genes from plants
that make them respond to light.

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:58.270
So we know that plants
do respond to light.

00:32:58.270 --> 00:33:00.420
A leaf will move toward the sun.

00:33:00.420 --> 00:33:02.660
Plants are phototropic.

00:33:02.660 --> 00:33:07.600
You could actually take the gene
that makes plants do that and put

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:13.790
that gene inside a neuron
inside the mammalian cortex.

00:33:13.790 --> 00:33:19.250 position:56%
And so when a light is shown on that
neuron, it will then actually fire.

00:33:19.250 --> 00:33:23.100
So you can set it up -- the details
get very complicated and I talk

00:33:23.100 --> 00:33:27.060
about them at length in my book,
"World Wide Mind", but you can set

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:30.290
up a neuron so that when you're
showing blue light on it,

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:33.990
that neuron will start to
fire and only that neuron.

00:33:33.990 --> 00:33:36.440
The other neurons around
it don't fire.

00:33:36.440 --> 00:33:40.470 position:56%
It's possible to make this
technique so specific you can choose

00:33:40.470 --> 00:33:46.100 position:56%
to fire only selecting neurons out
of a bunch of thousands or millions.

00:33:46.100 --> 00:33:50.900
Conversely, you can also use yellow
light to make your own stop firing.

00:33:50.900 --> 00:33:55.120
When you're showing a yellow
light, the neurons are inhibited.

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:58.530
So you can actually turn on
and off selected neurons just

00:33:58.530 --> 00:34:00.860
by showing new lights on them.

00:34:00.860 --> 00:34:06.700 position:56%
And a way to do this is to put light
emitting diodes underneath the skull

00:34:06.700 --> 00:34:10.500
on top of the brain where they
actually illuminate brain tissue

00:34:10.500 --> 00:34:14.830
with red and yellow light and
other wavelengths as well.

00:34:14.830 --> 00:34:18.660
So you actually get to control
neurons on the cortex of the brain

00:34:18.660 --> 00:34:22.580 position:56%
which is where most cognition takes
place without actually having to cut

00:34:22.580 --> 00:34:26.730
into the brain or to try to
send nanowires into the brain

00:34:26.730 --> 00:34:29.740
from the other direction
through the capillaries.

00:34:29.740 --> 00:34:31.920
So this is opening
up the possibility

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:36.180
of creating brain implants that
just sit on top of the brain.

00:34:36.180 --> 00:34:41.490
And let me show you a mouse to
whom this has actually been done.

00:34:41.490 --> 00:34:44.420
So this video, I'd like to
show it to you twice for you

00:34:44.420 --> 00:34:47.230
to really understand
what's going on.

00:34:47.230 --> 00:34:51.090
So you're going to see a mouse
[inaudible] plastic tank.

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:55.440
What you can't see is that there is
a fiber optic cable that is hanging

00:34:55.440 --> 00:35:00.780
down and going into the mouse's
brain; and that cable is being used

00:35:00.780 --> 00:35:06.390
to send blue light into the mouse's
motor cortex, or more accurately,

00:35:06.390 --> 00:35:09.930
into one-half of the
mouse's motor cortex.

00:35:09.930 --> 00:35:14.330
So when blue light illuminate,
half of the mouse's motor cortex

00:35:14.330 --> 00:35:16.970
that controls the arms
and legs on one side,

00:35:16.970 --> 00:35:19.570
both arms and legs start to run.

00:35:19.570 --> 00:35:23.370
Since the other ones are not
being stimulated, what happens?

00:35:23.370 --> 00:35:24.930
The mouse goes in a circle, right?

00:35:24.930 --> 00:35:29.150
If you think about it, if you could
only move your right arm and leg

00:35:29.150 --> 00:35:33.510
and you were on all fours, it
would end up going in a circle.

00:35:33.510 --> 00:35:35.330
So that's what's going on here.

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:39.440
So I'll play it again and watch
very carefully for the blue light

00:35:39.440 --> 00:35:43.420
that shines in the mouse's head
and as that blue light turns on,

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:46.880
the mouse will start to run
in a counterclockwise circle.

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:49.300
When the light is turned
off, the mouse will stop.

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:50.780
Okay, watch again.

00:35:50.780 --> 00:36:00.070 position:56%
Okay. So light's not on yet, so in
a second it's going to be turned on.

00:36:00.070 --> 00:36:03.940
Now, okay, it's running around
because it can't help it.

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:07.800
Its brain is being forced to fire,
the neurons in his motor cortex

00:36:07.800 --> 00:36:12.670
that make the legs on one side
move; and when it stops, it stops

00:36:12.670 --> 00:36:16.760
and so it looks up, you know, "What
the heck just happened [laughter]?"

00:36:16.760 --> 00:36:19.060
So it doesn't look dramatic.

00:36:19.060 --> 00:36:22.290
There's a mouse running around
in a circle, but what's dramatic

00:36:22.290 --> 00:36:25.150 position:56%
about it is, it's showing it the use

00:36:25.150 --> 00:36:30.610
of information light that's being
used to precisely control one thing

00:36:30.610 --> 00:36:33.620
that a mouse does and that's
doing one precise thing.

00:36:33.620 --> 00:36:35.280
It's running around in a circle.

00:36:35.280 --> 00:36:37.960
It's not having a convulsion,
it's not pressing levers,

00:36:37.960 --> 00:36:41.920
it's not feeling hungry; it's
just doing one particular thing.

00:36:41.920 --> 00:36:46.290 position:56%
So what is this telling us that when
you're beginning to figure out --

00:36:46.290 --> 00:36:48.160
and I really mean just beginning --

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:52.400
beginning to figure out how to
decompose activity in the brain

00:36:52.400 --> 00:36:54.700
to figure out what it means?

00:36:54.700 --> 00:36:58.480
When this neuron, that neuron and
this neuron and that neuron fire,

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:00.340
what does that correspond to?

00:37:00.340 --> 00:37:03.770
We're just trying to figure out
those kinds of relationships

00:37:03.770 --> 00:37:07.600
and here's an example of the paper
that came out a few years ago.

00:37:07.600 --> 00:37:11.080 position:56%
In the early [inaudible] of the
concepts of nest in the mouse brain.

00:37:11.080 --> 00:37:13.830
So to figure out which
neurons activate

00:37:13.830 --> 00:37:16.700
when the mouse sees its nest.

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:20.080
So the ultimate idea is that
all the things that we think

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:25.760
of as immaterial thought is
our ideas, our perceptions,

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:30.070
our feelings, our bodily
sensations, our hungers,

00:37:30.070 --> 00:37:33.710
all of these are ultimately
represented and caused

00:37:33.710 --> 00:37:38.100
by specific pattern of
neural activity in the brain.

00:37:38.100 --> 00:37:43.110
You know, in reality, it is
extraordinarily complicated.

00:37:43.110 --> 00:37:48.340
Researchers have found that when
animals like monkeys make but looks

00:37:48.340 --> 00:37:52.190
like the same motion, different
sets of neurons will fire.

00:37:52.190 --> 00:37:54.520
So it's clearly very complicated.

00:37:54.520 --> 00:37:58.390
It's not a simple as oh,
neurons X, Y, Z fire,

00:37:58.390 --> 00:37:59.840
that means that this is happening.

00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:02.730
The relationships are much
more complex than that.

00:38:02.730 --> 00:38:05.050
That's partly because the
brain is constantly changing

00:38:05.050 --> 00:38:07.410
and it's constantly learning.

00:38:07.410 --> 00:38:11.600
So, for example, when you
train a mouse to move its arm

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:14.360
in a certain way and
watch neurons fire.

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:17.840
If you then put a weight on
that monkey's arm so that it has

00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:21.010
to work a little bit harder
to make the same motion,

00:38:21.010 --> 00:38:24.890
you'll see different neurons fire
because the brain is adjusting,

00:38:24.890 --> 00:38:28.570
to learn how to make the arm
move the same way even though the

00:38:28.570 --> 00:38:30.970
situation has changed.

00:38:30.970 --> 00:38:34.480
So the neural code is not
[inaudible] a solid thing

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:38.310
like an alphabet or a language;
it is a constantly changing thing.

00:38:38.310 --> 00:38:40.990
And the challenge is trying to
figure out how to understand

00:38:40.990 --> 00:38:44.990
that well enough to be able
to actually intervene in it,

00:38:44.990 --> 00:38:49.410
to figure out what it means
and to make neurons fire

00:38:49.410 --> 00:38:54.460
to make the brain experience a
particular sensation or taste

00:38:54.460 --> 00:38:56.670
or hunger or thought or feeling.

00:38:56.670 --> 00:39:01.030
Now, if you think this
sounds completely outlandish,

00:39:01.030 --> 00:39:02.540
consider for a moment

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:07.380
that my cochlear implant is sending
electrical signals to my brain

00:39:07.380 --> 00:39:09.560
that makes my brain
believe that it's here.

00:39:09.560 --> 00:39:11.760
I'm completely deaf.

00:39:11.760 --> 00:39:16.160
I have no biological hearing
and yet researchers had figured

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:19.930
out the auditory code of the
brain well enough to enable me

00:39:19.930 --> 00:39:24.000
to hear something that sounds
pretty much like normal English.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:29.210
So to give [inaudible] details
[inaudible] optogenetics.

00:39:29.210 --> 00:39:34.040
So as I said before, it can fire
or inhibit just one type of neuron,

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:36.180
let's say, motor neurons,

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:41.190
that control the arm while
leaving all the others unaffected.

00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:45.230 position:56%
And because you're injecting viruses
into the tissue to insert the gene

00:39:45.230 --> 00:39:49.490
into those neurons, you can very
much limit where it happens just

00:39:49.490 --> 00:39:51.660
by only injecting the viruses

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:55.350
that carry those genes
into particular areas.

00:39:55.350 --> 00:39:59.560
And so with refinements, which I
talked about in "World Wide Mind,"

00:39:59.560 --> 00:40:04.190
it's potentially possible to
activate only specific neurons

00:40:04.190 --> 00:40:09.110
and to detect only, when to
detect which neurons fire

00:40:09.110 --> 00:40:11.680
when a given action
or a given perception

00:40:11.680 --> 00:40:13.800
or a given thought happens.

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:17.560
So optogenetics has really
transformed neuroscience.

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:22.390
It's allowed researchers to really
begin dissecting the actual neural

00:40:22.390 --> 00:40:25.270
basis of thought and action.

00:40:25.270 --> 00:40:28.440
So here's a paper that came out
just recently and got quite a lot

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:31.480
of press, you may have
heard about it.

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:33.680
In fact, I haven't
given you a reference

00:40:33.680 --> 00:40:36.510
because you can just find
it by Googling phrase like

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:40.460 position:56%
"brain-to-brain interphase real time
sharing," the paper will come up.

00:40:40.460 --> 00:40:42.880
It's an Open Access paper.

00:40:42.880 --> 00:40:47.670
And this was in the lab of Miguel
Nicolelis at Duke University,;

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:52.350
and he reported that he had
gotten one rat to be able

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:57.080
to send a mental signal to another
rat to tell that rat which lever

00:40:57.080 --> 00:40:59.940
to press, the right
one or the left one.

00:40:59.940 --> 00:41:03.610
Okay? So let's dig
into that a little bit.

00:41:03.610 --> 00:41:05.240
When I first read about the study,

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:07.740
here's what I thought
they were doing.

00:41:07.740 --> 00:41:12.770
So, they had two rats and they both
have arrays of electrodes implanted

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:17.210 position:56%
in their brains and those electrodes
can both detect neural activity

00:41:17.210 --> 00:41:19.350
and trigger neural activity.

00:41:19.350 --> 00:41:21.980
It goes either way.

00:41:21.980 --> 00:41:24.990
So what I thought they were doing
is they were having the sender rat

00:41:24.990 --> 00:41:27.810
pressing a left or
a right bar, okay,

00:41:27.810 --> 00:41:31.210
depending on which
light flashed above it,

00:41:31.210 --> 00:41:36.370
and then the computer picked up a
certain pattern of neural activity

00:41:36.370 --> 00:41:39.020
that they had previously
learned and corresponded

00:41:39.020 --> 00:41:41.760
to pressing, say, the left bar.

00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:44.520
And that they sent a
simple code, you know,

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:48.180
it's like a certain
sensation to another mouse

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:52.090
with an implanted electrode
array and that mouse had learned

00:41:52.090 --> 00:41:55.120
when I had this sensation,
I pressed the left bar,

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:57.950
when I had that sensation,
I pressed the right bar.

00:41:57.950 --> 00:42:00.290
That's what I thought it
was, so, I was like, oh,

00:42:00.290 --> 00:42:03.210
that's not such a big deal
because you just do that just

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:07.010
by implanting electrodes and
training a mouse to do something

00:42:07.010 --> 00:42:08.780
when it has a certain sensation.

00:42:08.780 --> 00:42:10.640
Big deal. So what?

00:42:10.640 --> 00:42:13.330
Well, I read the paper very
carefully a couple of times

00:42:13.330 --> 00:42:15.250 position:56%
and this is what's really happening.

00:42:15.250 --> 00:42:20.950
So the sender mouse, which is the
one on the left, presses the left

00:42:20.950 --> 00:42:24.400
or the right bar -- let's
say it's the left bar.

00:42:24.400 --> 00:42:28.350
The pattern neural activity that
corresponds to that is picked up

00:42:28.350 --> 00:42:33.730
and recorded and it's processed to
basically clean it up a little bit,

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:39.080
and then that actual data, the
cleaned-up version of that data,

00:42:39.080 --> 00:42:42.830
is sent to the receiver's brain.

00:42:42.830 --> 00:42:47.690
So whatever neural pattern fires,
whatever they detect in the sender,

00:42:47.690 --> 00:42:49.140
they clean it up a little bit

00:42:49.140 --> 00:42:51.680
and they send it to
the receiver's brain.

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:56.960
So the receiver mouse is getting
a slightly filtered version

00:42:56.960 --> 00:43:00.190
of what's actually going on
in the sender rat's brain.

00:43:00.190 --> 00:43:05.500
And if that mouse actually
presses the left bar,

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:10.450
the sender mouse gets a reward; the
sender mouse gets a drink of water,

00:43:10.450 --> 00:43:12.930
so that when the sender
mouse gets it right,

00:43:12.930 --> 00:43:15.630
it gets rewarded for that activity.

00:43:15.630 --> 00:43:19.270
So it learns, if I press the
bar this way, if I just do it

00:43:19.270 --> 00:43:22.410
in this certain way, I get rewards.

00:43:22.410 --> 00:43:26.600
So there is actually a kind of
circular communication going

00:43:26.600 --> 00:43:29.240
on here between the mice.

00:43:29.240 --> 00:43:31.300
Now, I started asking
some questions.

00:43:31.300 --> 00:43:35.840
The success rate of this
was between 60% and 72%,

00:43:35.840 --> 00:43:38.690
which is not actually incredibly
good when you think about that

00:43:38.690 --> 00:43:41.920
by chance alone you will
get a 50% success rate.

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:44.570
Okay? So clearly there
were lots of times

00:43:44.570 --> 00:43:48.450
when the sender pushed the left bar
and the receiver either did nothing

00:43:48.450 --> 00:43:52.800
or pressed the other bar, so
it's clearly not fool-proof yet.

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:56.370
You can kind of see this pattern
of [inaudible] up is both amazing

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:58.250
and underwhelming, right?

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:01.810
This idea comes up
over and over again,

00:44:01.810 --> 00:44:04.170
but it raises some very
interesting questions.

00:44:04.170 --> 00:44:08.750
So do the rats think they're
communicating or do they just think

00:44:08.750 --> 00:44:12.030
that stuff is happening in their
heads and they're pressing bars?

00:44:12.030 --> 00:44:15.490
And the paper really doesn't answer
that question as far as I can tell.

00:44:15.490 --> 00:44:16.960
Can the rats see each other?

00:44:16.960 --> 00:44:19.260
Do they actually know that
they are communicating?

00:44:19.260 --> 00:44:20.370
I'm not clear on that.

00:44:20.370 --> 00:44:24.360
The other question I think is
actually more interesting is

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:27.910
that the receiver rat feels that
it's responding to a signal;

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:30.680
is it thinking, "Oh, I'm
getting this kind of sensation,

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:35.190
I'm going to press the left bar,"
or, is it actually being forced

00:44:35.190 --> 00:44:38.710
to press the left bar because the
neurons in his brain [inaudible]

00:44:38.710 --> 00:44:43.020
when the left bar gets pressed is
actually -- are actually firing.

00:44:43.020 --> 00:44:46.960
So [inaudible] just pushing
that bar because it thinks just

00:44:46.960 --> 00:44:50.180
as if it had decided
to do it itself.

00:44:50.180 --> 00:44:52.550
So that's a very interesting
question.

00:44:52.550 --> 00:44:56.900
We may not know the answer to
that until we are able to get --

00:44:56.900 --> 00:44:59.240
stop working with rats and
start working with people

00:44:59.240 --> 00:45:01.070
because you can't interview
a rat and say, "Well,

00:45:01.070 --> 00:45:02.990
what do you think happened?"

00:45:02.990 --> 00:45:05.150
It raises all these very
interesting questions.

00:45:05.150 --> 00:45:08.280 position:56%
So in the paper, I was looking at --

00:45:08.280 --> 00:45:10.540
quoted you what it said at
the very end of the paper,

00:45:10.540 --> 00:45:14.410
which is kind of both mind
blowing and [inaudible] okay.

00:45:14.410 --> 00:45:20.530
So he says, "In theory, channel
accuracy," and this is the accuracy

00:45:20.530 --> 00:45:24.340 position:56%
of how well it works, "can be
increased if instead of [inaudible],

00:45:24.340 --> 00:45:30.480
a whole grid of multiple
reciprocally interconnected brains

00:45:30.480 --> 00:45:31.760
are employed."

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:34.320
So let's talk about wiring
together a whole bunch of rats.

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:35.540
All right.

00:45:35.540 --> 00:45:38.270
Well, what do you get from that?

00:45:38.270 --> 00:45:41.340
Such a computing structure
could define the first example

00:45:41.340 --> 00:45:45.490
of an organic computer capable
of solving heuristic problems

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:50.700
that would be deemed non-computable
by [inaudible] machine.

00:45:50.700 --> 00:45:53.570
Well, this will mean more
if you're a computer geek.

00:45:53.570 --> 00:45:59.800
Okay? But what they're saying
in plain English is that, A,

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:01.620
if you connect a whole bunch

00:46:01.620 --> 00:46:05.100
of rats together we think
something interesting is going

00:46:05.100 --> 00:46:07.350
to happen but we're not sure what.

00:46:07.350 --> 00:46:12.120
And they're suggesting that
maybe this interconnected set

00:46:12.120 --> 00:46:15.600
of rats will be able to do things
that rats have never been able

00:46:15.600 --> 00:46:18.480
to do before, whatever that is.

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:23.020 position:56%
So, I started thinking about,
"Well, could you do this to people?"

00:46:23.020 --> 00:46:28.840
And [inaudible] that the answer is,
in theory, yes, okay, in theory.

00:46:28.840 --> 00:46:30.720
There's obviously a lot
of technical challenges

00:46:30.720 --> 00:46:32.940
to solve, but in theory, yes.

00:46:32.940 --> 00:46:35.610
So let's say you had an
implanted optogenetic array

00:46:35.610 --> 00:46:39.610
in the left person's brain and
that person thinks of an apple,

00:46:39.610 --> 00:46:42.310
a certain set of neurons fire.

00:46:42.310 --> 00:46:45.240
So that person's implanted
array picks up that set

00:46:45.240 --> 00:46:46.640
of firings and decodes it.

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:49.620
Oh, this means a person
is thinking of an apple.

00:46:49.620 --> 00:46:54.080
And then sends a code over the
Internet which just consists

00:46:54.080 --> 00:46:57.120
of the word "apple," okay,
nothing very complicated,

00:46:57.120 --> 00:47:00.890 position:56%
just the word "apple", and
[inaudible] the array, picks that up

00:47:00.890 --> 00:47:04.890
and it knows which neurons to
activate in that person's brain

00:47:04.890 --> 00:47:06.460
so [background talking] you
then have the perception

00:47:06.460 --> 00:47:07.960
of seeing an apple.

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:12.340
So you've sent a perception
of seeing something

00:47:12.340 --> 00:47:16.150
through the Internet, these would
be literally two brains connected

00:47:16.150 --> 00:47:19.350
by this kind of Internet system.

00:47:19.350 --> 00:47:22.720
And in "World Wide Mind" I
called this "telempathy,"

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:26.850
to talk about the fact that this is
nonverbal information that's being

00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:30.370
sent, and that would be
the interesting thing.

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:33.740
Sending speech, well, we've
got a technology to do that,

00:47:33.740 --> 00:47:35.450
it's called a cell phone.

00:47:35.450 --> 00:47:38.550
What's more interesting is sending
things that we cannot now send

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:41.890
over the wires, feelings,
perceptions,

00:47:41.890 --> 00:47:45.250
sensations, ideas, eventually.

00:47:45.250 --> 00:47:46.290
So let me just [inaudible]
a whole bunch

00:47:46.290 --> 00:47:49.670
of long disclaimers as I wind down.

00:47:49.670 --> 00:47:52.020
We are still struggling to
understand the neural code.

00:47:52.020 --> 00:47:57.480
It is still essentially
impossible to just look at a brain

00:47:57.480 --> 00:48:01.920
at its neural firing and figure
out what that brain is doing.

00:48:01.920 --> 00:48:05.830
All we can really do now is
record a brain's activity

00:48:05.830 --> 00:48:09.890
as it does something where we know
what it's doing, pressing a lever,

00:48:09.890 --> 00:48:13.630
seeing an apple, and then, if we
see the brain doing that, again,

00:48:13.630 --> 00:48:18.300 position:56%
we figure, oh, the brain must be
seeing an apple or pressing a lever.

00:48:18.300 --> 00:48:21.580
It's a one-to-one correspondence.

00:48:21.580 --> 00:48:22.560
But there's no way as

00:48:22.560 --> 00:48:26.100
yet of understanding the
general code of the brain.

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:28.330
If this electrode -- [inaudible]
this neuron, that neuron,

00:48:28.330 --> 00:48:30.670
that neuron, that neuron,
these neurons fire,

00:48:30.670 --> 00:48:34.550
all that means is a person
thinking of the "Wizard of Oz".

00:48:34.550 --> 00:48:35.350
[Inaudible], okay?

00:48:35.350 --> 00:48:39.480
And I think [inaudible]
is stupendously difficult.

00:48:39.480 --> 00:48:43.230 position:56%
It's kind of like Robert Goddard
launching his first rocket that went

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:46.300
up 30 feet and then extrapolating
from that [inaudible] say, "Oh,

00:48:46.300 --> 00:48:47.400
we'll be able to get to the moon."

00:48:47.400 --> 00:48:52.260 position:56%
Well, we could, it's just that we're
still at that Robert Goddard stage.

00:48:52.260 --> 00:48:54.850
I also argued in "World Wide Mind"

00:48:54.850 --> 00:48:57.770
that this technology would not
work unless you had [inaudible]

00:48:57.770 --> 00:48:59.580
communicative context.

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:03.490
So unless person A and person B
are in a context where thinking

00:49:03.490 --> 00:49:06.980
